    <h2>Publications</h2>
    <div class="cfix">
            <div class="figure">
              










</div>
    <dl class="ico ico-text">
      <dt>Title</dt><dd>The Jewish Annotated New Testament</dd><dt>Author</dt><dd>(Ed) Amy-Jill Levine and Marc Zvi Brettler</dd><dt>Publisher</dt><dd> Oxford University Press</dd><dt>Description</dt><dd>This is the first edition of the New Testament that addresses its Jewish background and the culture from which it grew, from a Jewish perspective.</dd></dl>
          </div>
        <div class="cfix">
            <div class="figure">
              










</div>
    <dl class="ico ico-text">
      <dt>Title</dt><dd>Body Broken for a Broken People: Divorce, Remarriage, and the Eucharist</dd><dt>Author</dt><dd>Francis J. Moloney, SDB</dd><dt>Publisher</dt><dd>Garratt Publishing</dd><dt>Description</dt><dd>In a fresh reading of the New Testament eucharistic texts, Francis Moloney traces a constant theme of the presence of Jesus to those in need. He then examines current Catholic practice on the admission of the divorced and remarried to the Eucharist. What is practised is a late and distorted tradition, he argues. He asks the Church to return to authentic Catholic Tradition. The book, an extensively revised version of a book originally published by Collins Dove in 1990, <a class="external" href="http://www.garrattpublishing.com.au/product/9781925009804/" target="_blank" title="Moloney book details">will be published</a> in time to enter the lively and indeed heated international Catholic discussion on this topic, in anticipation of the October 2015 <a class="external" href="http://www.usccb.org/issues-and-action/marriage-and-family/2014-2015-synods-of-bishops-on-the-family.cfm" target="_blank" title="Synod of Bishops Oct 2015">Synod of Bishops on the Family</a>, to be held in Rome.  </dd></dl>
          </div>
        <div class="cfix">
            <div class="figure">
              










</div>
    <dl class="ico ico-text">
      <dt>Title</dt><dd>Judaism in Contemporary Thought: Traces and Influence</dd><dt>Author</dt><dd>Agata Bielik-Robson, Adam Lipszyc</dd><dt>Publisher</dt><dd> Routledge Jewish Studies Series</dd><dt>Description</dt><dd>The central aim of this collection is to trace the presence of Jewish tradition in contemporary philosophy. </dd></dl>
